	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=736'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#CC6600;font-weight:bold; '>Paelix</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Master<br>
			
				Posts: 276<br>
				
				Registered: 03-01-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=736'>







<img src="/eq/i/icons/Classes/cleric.gif" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&message.id=10413#M10413">20</a> of 95
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 156 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<P>My idea is rather odd, but I would almost like to see tradeskills and recipes to be changed to be like spells, but requiring minimum tradeskill level rather than character level.&nbsp; Recipes could range from basic items (such as a sword, a robe, a staff, and so on) through methods of improving said items (call them techniques perhaps.)&nbsp; </P>
<P>So a blacksmith starts off with a few vendor-buyable formulae, simple things like tools and possibly daggers, spears, axes, etc.&nbsp; Nothing fancy.&nbsp; Initially they would get a "recipe" that gives them the ability to work with bronze, but they would lack the knowledge of being able to work with other materials.&nbsp; More advanced recipes would be a combination of dropped formulas or found only on very remote vendors (and made buyable but nodrop, and only buyable by someone with sufficient skill "I will not sell you this you fool!&nbsp; You lack the skill to make it!"</P>
<P>Materials Recipes: What you make the item out of.&nbsp; Obviously buyable in some cases and in certain places, droppable in others.</P>
<P>Form Recipes: Basic items, what your final product is.&nbsp; These would require a "reagent" being the appropriate mold, pattern, and so on.</P>
<P>Appearance Recipes: Its final graphical appearance, including the ability to add particle effects, colors, and so on.&nbsp; Each of these augmentations would require appropriate reagents ranging from dyes to whatever expensive or rare drops deemed appropriate.</P>
<P>Augmentation Recipes: Making the final item interesting, magical, and so on.&nbsp; All of these would require dropped and/or vendor buyable (cash sink) reagents.&nbsp; The more powerful augmentations, capable of producing items equivilent to raid drops, would naturally require rare drops from appropriate areas.</P>
<DIV>A form would have a basic skill required for it, modified by its material.&nbsp; Appearance and Augmentation recipes would add to the difficulty.&nbsp; Based on material, a given item could only accept a certain number, and maximum rating, of enhancement.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>A bronze longsword might be able to accept a "damage augment" a "magic augment" and a "speed augment" before reaching the limits of the material to accept anything else.&nbsp; If a basic long sword was 5/30, the bronze longsword in this example might be magic, dmg 7, and dly 27.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>What is the final objective: Introduce a system of "building" items.&nbsp; Bronze items only taking a few potential enhancements, then iron, then steel, then fine steel, then velium, and so on.&nbsp; Making an item that isn't trivial gives an automatic skill increase.&nbsp; The challenge moves from "can I avoid carpal tunnel long enough wihle researching recipes on eqtraders" to "I need to find the gem of firey uberness in order to make a guildie magician a staff that will focus their fire pets."&nbsp; The benefit to the tradeskill community becomes a system where not everyone can make everything, and those that work the hardest to find and collect formulas can make some extremely varied and customized items.&nbsp; A high level smith could choose between making caster-wearable plate armor (low AC, weak combat stats, but basically there for the graphics), to something mid-range for hybrids, to very impressive "tank" armor that is little more than a ton of ac/hp.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Rare augmentation recipes can include knowing how to apply focus effects to items, flowing thought, vengeance, regeneration, skill mods and bonuses (hmmm....a plate BP that has decent AC but includes defense skill +20 on it too....)&nbsp; Certain materials could convey innate benefits (such as sword made of fine steel would innately have better dmg/dly than one of bronze.)&nbsp; Then, make ALL tradeskilled items droppable, but with recommended levels on them (varied based on materials and augmentations), and retool all existing droppable items with similar recommended levels, and you solve the problem of low level characters overpowered for their environment, you restore some semblance of balance between the insane power of melee twinks vs. caster twinks (or worse, non-twinked casters), and provide an incentive for tradeskillers at all levels to make items knowing that people can and will buy them, especially if they have interesting and unique augmentations.</DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							EQ1:<br>Zarros, High Elf Cleric<br>Zanros, Iksar Beastlord<br>Avante Guarde of the Saryrn Server
							</div>
								
		</td></tr>
